From my window today. One of the memories most engraved in my brain and to think my son wasn’t yet born and it was the first day of kindergarten for my daughter. For us here in NY it’s still very personal.

For GQ Middle East’s issue in collaboration with Ruba Abu-Nimah (@ruba), the legendary creative director discusses how she spent her entire life “hiding in plain sight”. 

“This issue is dedicated to future generations of people like me. The next generation will be loud and proud. They will uphold and strengthen our culture, our language, our roots and our heritage.”

Ruba Abu-Nimah
December Issue Guest Editor 

Explore a very special issue of GQ Middle East guest-edited by @ruba on our website. Stay tuned.

Creative Director Ruba Abu-Nimah (@ruba) prefers to call herself a graphic designer. In a world oversaturated with creative directors, her work and ethos stands apart for its attunement to craftsmanship, artistry, and analog skills—but after decades in the luxury industry, offering her insight to names like @elleusa, @balenciaga, @shiseido, @revlon, and @tiffanyandco, she has an intuitive understanding of audiences and cultural shifts. 

Sitting down with @chrimichael, she articulates her ideas on artistic expression, from formative years spent growing up in London’s punk and design scenes to her present-day love for Andy Warhol’s democratizing practice. Balancing a humble, nonelitist approach with a hard-to-match know-how, Abu-Nimah looks to youth culture and a sense of rebelliousness to inform what’s contemporary now. 

Listen to the full episode at the link in bio.

#WhatsContemporaryNow #RubaAbuNimah

What does it mean to be Arab, North African, Middle Eastern in the West? 

41 emerging faces from the diaspora are captured through the lens of acclaimed photographer @SharifHamza with creative direction by @Ruba and styled by @malinajoseph.

“What’s so interesting is that the three of us got emotional on that day because we realised we had never seen that much representation in one room, in one place, at any point in our lives” says Ruba Abu-Nimah (@ruba). “The intention here is to exemplify us as a people in the West with a true identity.”

Thank you @gqmiddleeast and @ahmadaswaid for giving me the opportunity to collaborate on this December issue. It was not only a pleasure but timely. I also thank everyone who contributed and came together to share their talents and passions. None of us can achieve anything alone. It really does take a village. I also wanted to share my editors letter here. Sharing such a personal note is never easy but, as they say, if not now then when?

GQ Middle East’s latest guest-edited issue is a special one with a very important message: the power of unification for Arabs everywhere. Editor-in-Chief @ahmadaswaid speaks with the legendary creative director and guest editor @ruba, about collaboration, friendship, and voices of the people.

“Ruba and I have long discussed joining forces, and the timing of this happening couldn’t have been more kismet to reflect the paradigm shift we are living in,” says @ahmadaswaid.

Head to our website to read their full conversation.

41 faces from the SWANA diaspora – captured through the lens of Sharif Hamza (@sharifhamza) – come together to share what it means to be Arab, North African, Middle Eastern in the West.
